    {
      "id": "319e3c7fe1d20d9f3ba56f7649f5790693fdac39",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 118,
        "name": "Mikhail Pershin",
        "email": "mpershin@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "tappro"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-09 20:15:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nthis is not needed because local storage doesn't use sequence in which old files were created. FID_SEQ_LOCAL_FILE is used only for nameless objects created by dt_object_find_or_create() and names for them are created by OSD compat code. The simplest way to check that this sequence will not be used occasionally in local storage would be just assertion checking that sequence is not FID_SEQ_LOCAL_FILE.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "fed2e1bf5499f818b41dd3f199a056e95d846855",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-05-10 01:22:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe trouble is that, for OI scrub, it thought that some local files (such as lfsck_bookmark, lfsck_namespace, PENDING) should use fixed/reserve FIDs with \"seq = FID_SEQ_LOCAL_FILE\", but the real FIDs assigned to them are with \"seq = FID_SEQ_LOCAL_NAME\". Such difference will cause OI scrub confused.\n\nSo either we make OI scrub to know above changes, or adjust the create logic to assign fixed FIDs to them.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "aac5125b7ee37427069cb5097a085270a19c2e06",
      "author": {
